<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911010-0133</DOCNO><DOCID>911010-0133.</DOCID><HL>   Comsat Unit Signs Up   Two TV Broadcasters   For Latest Satellite</HL><DATE>10/10/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   CQ I.RAI</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><RE>DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA (DC)EUROPE (EU)ITALY (ITA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   GENEVA -- Communications Satellite Corp.'s World Systemsunit signed agreements with two international broadcasterswhich will be the first customers for one of the world'snewest and most powerful communications satellites.   The customers are Brightstar Ltd., an internationalsatellite carrier based in London, and a partnership ofRadiotelevisione Italiana (RAI), which is based in Rome, andKayFourCast S.A., based here.</LP><TEXT>   The satellite is the newest of those planned by theInternational Telecommunications Satellite Organization. Itallows broadcasters to transmit directly between Europe,North and South America by using only one tiny earth stationon each end of a broadcast transmission path.   Brightstar and the RAI partnership said they will eachlease two of the satellite's 16 transponders -- a combinedtransmitter and receiver that responds automatically to aspecific signal -- for 10 years and five years, respectively.   The RAI partnership will use the satellite to beam TVprogramming to households in the U.S. and South America. Theservice will officially begin on Oct. 12, 1992, the 500thanniversary of Christopher Columbus' voyage to America --assuming the satellite launch is successful.   Brightstar, a carrier of TV programming between Europe andNorth America, will beam daily news and other programs tosmall-dish rooftop antennae.   Bruce Crocket, president and chief operating officer ofComsat, which is based in Washington, D.C., said new serviceswill provide most of the company's growth. Comsat's mobileservices, including the transmission of public phone calls oncruise ships and mobile tracking systems, are growing morethan 30% a year. &quot;We'll do in excess of a half billiondollars this year in annual revenue and have earnings in the$3 a share range.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>